I don't understand these tests or why we need them to be internal. What's tested here that's not tested in TestHandleHTTP? Is it the time stamp?

If it's the time, we should consider whether we want an entirely separate test file and package for them. We could validate times by injecting a clock/time function or by ensuring the field is present with a parsable, non-empty time. Alternatively we could put all tests in the same package.

If we don't want an exported clock (because of drag), we can include an exported time function field and use this internal package to provide a setter:

```
package healthz

type HealthHandler struct {
	mutex          sync.Mutex
	HealthCheckers map[string]HealthChecker

	now func() time.Time
}

// NewHealthHandler returns a new HealthHandler instance.
func NewHealthHandler() *HealthHandler {
	return &HealthHandler{
		HealthCheckers: map[string]HealthChecker{},
		now: time.Now,
	}
}
...
use now instead of time.Now()
```

Then in the internal_test.go file, just declare a method on the health handler to set the function:
```
func (h *HealthHandler) SetNow(now func() time.Time) { h.now = now }
```

The tests can then implement a broken clock function, we have a private injection point, and the tests remain in a separate package. (Overkill? Probably for this.)
